    </figure>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00003">
    <title>Working with Numeric and Text Data in a Sheets Cell</title>
    <para id="para-00006">Copying the formatting from an existing table is helpful, but it is not always an option. In some cases, you will need to create a table from scratch. The first step is to establish the headers in the first row (<link target-id="fig-00003"/>a). Based on the headers, you can then choose the most appropriate format for the data (<link target-id="fig-00003"/>b).</para>
    <figure id="fig-00003" class="scaled-down">
    <title/>
    <media alt="Part a shows a blank spreadsheet with words in Row 1. Cells A1 through A10 are selected. The 123 icon is selected on the toolbar and the pop up window lists: Automatic (selected with a checkmark), Plain text, Number, Percent, Scientific, Accounting, Financial, Currency, Currency (rounded), Date, Time, Date time, Duration, Custom currency, Custom date and time, Custom number format. Part b shows Cell A1 selected with Fill color selected from the Action Bar. The drop down shows “Reset” and 60 different color circles. No color is shown as selected.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OSX_BCA_09_06_DATA01.jpg"/></media>
    <caption>Creating a table from scratch requires many steps. First, enter your headers in the first row. (a) Then, format each column for the type of data it will contain. Adjust the column width when necessary. Format your header row by bolding and centering the content. (b) Finally, add the background fill from the custom color menu. (attribution: Copyright Rice University, OpenStax, under CC BY 4.0 license)</caption>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00007">The format types Sheets uses are similar to the ones Excel uses. <link target-id="table-00001"/> compares the formats between Sheets and Excel. The names differ slightly, but many mean almost the same thing. There are minor differences like the order the format types appear in the menu (see [link]Figure 09_02_NUMER01[/link]), and there are some formats that are unique to Sheets. Sheets has the “Financial,” “Currency rounded,” “Date time,” and “Duration” formats that are not available in Excel.</para>
