    <note class="link-to-learning" id="note-00002">
    <para id="para-00011">The help forums for Sheets contain a short introduction to all the types of graphs you can build. They describe the use of each of the graphs, previews, and short step-by-step instructions. Go to <link url="https://openstax.org/l/78GoogleGraph">Google’s support page on the different graph types</link> to learn more.</para>
    </note>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00005">
    <title>Page Layout and Review Menus</title>
    <para id="para-00012">Sheets does not have menus that directly compare to the Page Layout and Review tabs in Excel, but it does have many of the same features. One feature Sheets does not have is Page Setup. The items in the Page Setup command group such as margins and page orientation are managed in the <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00018">Print Setting</term> in Google. Similar to the Themes command group in Excel, Sheets has a <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00019">Theme</term> option found in the Format menu (<link target-id="fig-00007"/>a). Excel’s Page Layout tab also has the Background command that allows you to choose an image for the background of your worksheet. This feature is partly available in Sheets in the Insert menu, which allows you to insert an “Image in cell” or “Image over cells” (<link target-id="fig-00007"/>b). The result of placing an image in a cell is shown in <link target-id="fig-00007"/>c. The inserted image (either in a cell or over cells) sits on top of the information in the cells, unlike in Excel, where the image is in the background. The other functions, like moving an object forward or backward, adding gridlines, or scaling settings, are partly available in Sheets. You can insert objects such as Google Draw files, Google Forms, charts, and images into the worksheets, but moving them around may be more cumbersome and less robust compared with Excel.</para>
    <figure id="fig-00007" class="scaled-down">
    <title/>
    <media alt="Part a shows A1:G1 selected. Across the top, the Format tab is selected and the drop down shows: Theme (New), Number, Bold, Italic, Underline, Strikethrough, Font size, and Align. In Part b, cell D1 is selected and the Insert tab is selected. The menu that is shown includes: Row above, Row below, Column left, Column right, Cells and shift down, Cells and shift right, Chart, Image and Drawing. Image is selected; the menu that shows to the right includes: Image in cell (new) and Image over cells. Part c shows an image of a tablet screen inserted into cell D1 on the spreadsheet, filling the entire cell.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/OSX_BCA_09_06_LAYOUT01.jpg"/></media>
    <caption>Page layout features in Sheets differ somewhat from those in Excel. (a) Themes are used to set a color scheme and/or font type for your spreadsheet. (b) You can insert an image in a single cell or over all of the cells in a worksheet. (c) Inserting an image in a single cell fills the cell with the image. (attribution: Copyright Rice University, OpenStax, under CC BY 4.0 license)</caption>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00013">The review features in Sheets differ somewhat from the Review tab commands in Excel. Sheets allows you to insert a comment (<link target-id="fig-00008"/>a) and view all the comments on the document by clicking on the <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00020">Comment History</term> button on the top (<link target-id="fig-00008"/>b). The <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00021">Tools menu</term> in Sheets has a spelling and grammar check (<link target-id="fig-00008"/>c).</para>
    <figure id="fig-00008">
    <title/>
    <media alt="Part a shows Rows 6, 7, and 8 selected. The Insert tab is selected and the drop down menu includes: 3 Rows above, 3 Rows below, 3 Columns left, 3 Columns right, Cells and shift down, Cells and shift right, Chart, Image, Drawing, Form, Function, Insert Link, Checkbox, and comment. Comment is selected. Part b shows an open window with drop down menus for All and All sheets at the top and Start a discussion and a green “Add comment” button at the bottom. Part c shows the spreadsheet with cells C6-C8 and D6-D8 selected. The Tools tab is selected and the menu shows: Create a form, AppSheet, Script editor, Macros, Spelling, Enable autocomplete, Notification rules, Protect sheet, and Accessibility settings. Spelling is selected and to the right Spell check and Personal dictionary are shown.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/OSX_BCA_09_06_REVIEW01.jpg"/></media>
    <caption>Some review features in Sheets are similar to those of Excel. (a) Comments are available in the Insert menu. (b) You can also review all comments in a workbook. (c) The spelling and grammar check are in the Tools menu. (attribution: Copyright Rice University, OpenStax, under CC BY 4.0 license)</caption>
    </figure>
    </section>
    <section class="section-summary" id="sect-00006">
    <title>Summary</title>
    <list id="list-00002">
    <item>The copy-and-paste function in Sheets works the same way as in Excel and allows the user to use the structure of an existing table to create a new one. Users can then manipulate the table by inserting columns or rows.</item>
    <item>To create a new table, first create header rows and then format the cells below it based on their contents. Then, as you add text or numbers, Sheets will automatically format them based on the type of data.</item>
    <item>Basic graphs require selecting the data for analysis and then inserting a graph. Sheets chooses the type of graph based on the type of data. You can change the graph type using the sidebar.</item>
    <item>Sheets has many of the same page layout and review features as Excel, with the major difference being the location of the tools in the interface.</item>
    </list>
    </section>
